{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_0","type":"agent_message","text":"final_filename: p23.cir\n\nObjective: Build a startup-capable single-supply Wien Bridge oscillator using VDD = 5 V and output node Vout. The transient analysis must show a visible sustained periodic oscillation at Vout during `.tran 1u 5m`, especially in the latter half of the waveform.\n\nTopology: Use a non-inverting op-amp-style gain stage biased around mid-supply, with a Wien Bridge positive feedback network from Vout to the non-inverting input. Use a separate resistive negative feedback path setting closed-loop gain slightly above 3 at startup, then limit amplitude gently with antiparallel diodes or MOS-connected nonlinear elements in the feedback leg. This is a topology-level redesign from weak-loop attempts: use a clean single-ended voltage amplifier macro built from dependent sources or a transistor/op-amp gain stage, not a marginal complementary-input core.\n\nRequired nodes:\nVout must be the oscillator output node.\nNo external input nodes are required.\n\nRequired supplies and references:\nUse `VDD vdd 0 DC 5`.\nCreate a mid-supply reference node, for example `Vmid`, using two equal resistors from vdd to ground and decouple it with a capacitor to ground. The op-amp input common mode and feedback network must be centered around Vmid, not ground, because this is a 5 V single-supply oscillator.\n\nCore signal path:\nThe amplifier output is Vout.\nThe non-inverting input node, e.g. `Vinp`, receives frequency-selective positive feedback through the Wien network:\n- Series branch from Vout to Vinp: capacitor then resistor, or resistor then capacitor.\n- Shunt branch from Vinp to Vmid: resistor and capacitor in parallel.\nUse equal R and equal C values for the Wien bridge so its phase shift is near zero and attenuation is about 1/3 at oscillation frequency.\n\nRecommended Wien values:\nUse R = 10 kOhm and C = 10 nF for both Wien arms.\nExpected oscillation frequency is approximately:\nf0 = 1 / (2*pi*R*C) ≈ 1.59 kHz.\nThis gives several cycles within 5 ms and should be easy for the evaluator to detect.\n\nAmplifier and negative feedback:\nUse an op-amp-like high-gain voltage-controlled voltage source or a simple transistor gain stage with enough gain. The easiest robust netlist-first implementation is:\n- High-gain differential VCVS sensing `Vinp` and `Vinn`.\n- Output limited or biased so Vout swings around Vmid within the 0 to 5 V rails.\n- If using ideal controlled sources, include output resistance/load capacitance so transient behavior is well-conditioned.\n\nSet the negative feedback divider from Vout to Vinn to Vmid for a non-inverting closed-loop gain slightly greater than 3 at startup:\nGain = 1 + Rf/Rg.\nChoose Rg = 10 kOhm from Vinn to Vmid.\nChoose Rf effective startup value around 22 kOhm to 24 kOhm from Vout to Vinn, giving gain about 3.2 to 3.4.\nAdd nonlinear stabilization so effective gain drops toward 3 as amplitude grows. A practical implementation:\n- Put a main feedback resistor, e.g. 22 kOhm to 24 kOhm, from Vout to Vinn.\n- Add antiparallel diodes or diode-connected MOSFET/resistor branch in parallel with part of the feedback path so large signals reduce gain gently.\nAvoid hard clipping as the only amplitude control; it can prevent clean periodicity.\n\nStartup requirements:\nInitialize internal op-amp input nodes with a slight mismatch so the evaluator can start oscillation. For example:\n`.ic V(Vinp)=2.51 V(Vinn)=2.49 V(Vout)=2.5`\nDo not leave Vinp or Vinn floating. Vinp must be connected by the Wien bridge to Vout and Vmid. Vinn must be connected by the negative feedback divider to Vout and Vmid.\n\nBiasing assumptions:\nVout should idle near 2.5 V and oscillate around 2.5 V.\nThe gain stage must have enough small-signal loop gain to overcome the Wien network attenuation at startup.\nIf MOSFETs are used, connect each bulk to its source and respect NMOS Vth = 0.7 V, PMOS Vth = -0.7 V. Prefer nominal sizing unless needed for gain.\nIf a behavioral or dependent-source op-amp is used, keep it explicitly powered or rail-limited to 0 V and 5 V if supported by the simulator.\n\nAnalysis:\nInclude exactly the required transient analysis:\n`.tran 1u 5m`\n\nExpected verification behavior:\nVout should develop a sinusoidal or lightly compressed periodic waveform centered near 2.5 V.\nThe latter half of the transient should have clearly detectable peaks, non-trivial amplitude, and a dominant frequency near 1.6 kHz.\nA target usable Vout amplitude is at least several hundred millivolts peak-to-peak; 1 Vpp to 3 Vpp is acceptable as long as it remains periodic and within the 0 to 5 V supply range.\n\nOutput constraints:\nThe final netlist must contain node `Vout`.\nUse no hidden subcircuits or undefined models.\nDo not rely on commented-out devices or floating startup nodes.\nThe oscillator must be self-contained with explicit VDD, Vmid generation, gain stage, Wien feedback network, amplitude stabilization, `.ic` startup asymmetry, and `.tran 1u 5m`."}}
